data.content:
Yes! A few better options in MSTest:

**Simplest: `[DataRow]` for inline constants**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**Strongly-typed: `DynamicData` with tuples (MSTest v3+)**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key differences:**

| Approach | Type safety | Dynamic data | Readability |
|---|---|---|---|
| `DataRow` | ✅ | ❌ (constants only) | Best for few cases |
| `DynamicData` + tuples | ✅ | ✅ | Clean + type-safe |
| `DynamicData` + `object[]` | ❌ | ✅ | Error-prone |

**Recommendation:** Use `[DataRow]` when your values are compile-time constants (like here). Switch to `DynamicData` with tuples when you need computed or complex test data. Both eliminate the `object[]` boxing and give you compile-time type checking.
